New Hope for India
Cambridge, USA — India's latest elections may be the most significant positive economic event since 2014.
Indian voters decisively rejected the Congress Party, which has almost always ruled India since its independence from Britain in 1947.
They may be happy with this decision.
Sonia Gandhi, the widow of former Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi and the Congress Party's leader, has been ruling since 1998, while Prime Minister Singh has been nothing more than a puppet.
Under her leadership, the Congress Party pursued populist agendas, increasing transfer payments, which caused India's annual economic growth rate to fall below 4% in 2013.
The per capita GDP still hovers around $4,000, less than half of China's.
The newly elected Prime Minister Narendra Modi promised during the campaign to bring rapid employment and income growth across India, just as he did when he served as Chief Minister of Gujarat.
Under Modi's leadership, Gujarat became a business-friendly state, with expanded economic activities and attracted commercial investments from both within and outside India.
A significant feature of the latest election was that Modi's Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) secured an absolute majority in the Lok Sabha, which can be considered an unprecedented achievement in India.
Therefore, Modi does not need to compromise with any national or regional parties to pursue his legislative agenda.
Two key officials will help Modi with the economic plan.
Arun Jaitley, the new finance minister, has extensive political experience and previously held a ministerial position in the previous BJP government.
Jaitely is also renowned as a strategist known for his sympathetic approach to commercial interests.
Raghuram Rajan will continue to serve as the Governor of the Reserve Bank of India. Rajan is an outstanding economist, and during his tenure as Governor, he demonstrated a desire to reduce India's high double-digit annual inflation rate and attempted to reform some of the inherent productivity constraints in India's financial sector.
The measures needed to stimulate economic growth will take time to be implemented and yield results.
But if you want to know whether the new government is taking action to achieve faster long-term growth, you should examine whether progress has been made in the following ten policy areas.
Education.
Although India has outstanding higher education and technical institutions, only a small portion of people can access the opportunities these institutions provide, because India's primary and secondary education is very backward.
Only 60% of Indian adults have literacy levels equivalent to primary school.
The teachers themselves have poor educational backgrounds and lack motivation, with many teachers never even appearing at their schools.
Infrastructure.
India needs better roads and ports to efficiently transport products throughout the country and around the world.
The recent expansion of private airlines and airports indicates that private enterprises can also play a role in this area.
Fiscal integration.
Large budget deficits absorb national savings, which could have been used to expand business investment. Budget deficits lead to an increase in national debt that can only be financed through future taxation.
Privatization.
Manufacturing and other industrial enterprises owned by the Indian government operate inefficiently, often resulting in the consumption of national savings.
Selling these enterprises directly helps accelerate economic growth.
Eliminate subsidies.
Subsidies for electricity and energy lead to wasteful overconsumption and increased fiscal deficits.
Although these subsidies are politically difficult to remove, they should be replaced with cash transfers. Currently, India's cash transfer system is highly efficient due to the remarkable new fingerprint-based cash transfer system.
Agricultural reform.
Under the current system, the government purchases, stores, and distributes agricultural products.
The result is a large surplus of goods stored in warehouses, while production incentives are misdirected.
Agricultural markets should be privatized.
Property rights and zoning regulations.
As long as you have been to Mumbai or other large Indian cities, you will see that zoning restrictions lead to poor land use in urban areas, constraining the initial dilution.
Unclear property rights, especially agricultural property rights, prevent industrialization in rural areas.
Relax restrictions on foreign investment.
Currently, foreign enterprises cannot become the majority shareholders of banks and insurance companies.
Relaxing these restrictions can strengthen the financial sector and play an important role in economic growth.
Tax reform.
India's complex central and state sales tax system distorts domestic trade.
The debate on replacing these taxes with a national value-added tax and adopting a divided taxation system has been ongoing for a long time, and it should now enter the implementation phase.
Corruption.
High-level corruption cases have damaged economic confidence and hindered officials' decision-making.
India is also deeply affected by petty corruption, with bribery having become a common feature in all business and personal transactions.
The government should severely punish high-level corruption and curb petty corruption through a new cash transfer system.
Driven by strong growth and expectations of increased profits, India's stock market has risen by 20% this year.
Now, Modi and the BJP need to prove to the world that they can fulfill their campaign promises.
